rogel.io.fopl.formulas

Class Predicate

  • java.lang.Object
    • rogel.io.fopl.formulas.Formula
      • rogel.io.fopl.formulas.Predicate
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Expression, Unifiable

    public final class Predicate
extends Formula
implements Unifiable
    A Predicate names a relation between Terms in a domain of discourse.

    A Predicate may be thought of as an Expression that may be true or false depending on the values of the terms it describes. It can also be thought of as an operator or function that returns a boolean value.

    Predicate: X -> [true, false]

    In this implementation, each Predicate that is declared (i.e. constructed) is true by virtue of its construction.

    Author:
    recardona

    • Constructor Detail

      • Predicate

        public Predicate(java.lang.String name,
         Term... terms)
        Constructs an n-ary true-valued Predicate with the given name. A 0-ary Predicate is used to represent a propositional symbol. The arity of this Predicate depends on the number of Terms added.

        If the name is a String that did not already exist within the domain of discourse (i.e. was already defined as a Symbol), then a new Symbol is created and added to the domain of discourse.

        Parameters:
        name - The name of the Predicate, not null.
        terms - The terms this Predicate describes, not null.

      • Predicate

        public Predicate(Symbol symbol,
         Term... terms)
        Constructs an n-ary true-valued Predicate with the given Symbol. A 0-ary Predicate is used to represent a propositional symbol. The arity of this Predicate depends on the number of Terms added.
        Parameters:
        symbol - The Symbol that represents this Predicate within the domain of discourse, not null.
        terms - The terms this Predicate describes, not null.

      • unify

        public Substitution unify(Unifiable unifiable,
                 Substitution substitution)
        Description copied from interface: Unifiable
        Attempts to find the Substitution that unifies (makes syntactically equivalent) this Unifiable Object with the parameter Unifiable Object, given an existing set of Substitutions. If no such Substitution exists, this method returns null.

        This method is commutative: calling u1.unify(u2, s) is equivalent to calling u2.unify(u1, s).

        Specified by:
        unify in interface Unifiable
        Parameters:
        unifiable - the Object to attempt to unify with, not null.
        substitution - the existing set of Substitutions to work with, not null.
        Returns:
        a Substitution that unifies this Object with the parameter Unifiable, or null if no Substitution exists.

      • hashCode
